# UI Component Customization Guidelines

To maintain upgradeability and cleanly separate application-specific design/logic from primitive components:

## 1. No Direct Edits to Shadcn Primitives

- **Rule:** Never modify files directly inside `src/lib/components/ui/`.
- **Reason:** These are imported Shadcn-Svelte primitive components. Direct modifications will be overwritten or cause merge conflicts when components are updated or re-installed via the CLI.

## 2. Extend/Wrap Components in `src/lib/components/app/`

- **Rule:** If you need customized behavior, specific styling variants, or composed elements based on Shadcn primitives, create a new custom component under `src/lib/components/app/` (e.g., `src/lib/components/app/custom-button.svelte`).
- **Example:**

  ```svelte
  <script lang="ts">
  	import type { Snippet } from 'svelte';
  	import { Button, type ButtonProps } from '$lib/components/ui/button';

  	let { children, ...restProps }: { children?: Snippet } & ButtonProps = $props();
  </script>

  <!-- Wrap the primitive and apply app-specific enhancements -->
  <Button {...restProps}>
  	{@render children?.()}
  </Button>
  ```

## 3. Typed Styling & `ClassValue`

- **Rule:** For component styling customization, always use type-safe classes leveraging `ClassValue` from `svelte/elements`. Avoid `any` types for props; instead, use Svelte element attribute types (e.g., `HTMLAttributes<HTMLDivElement>`, `HTMLButtonAttributes` from `svelte/elements`) or specific component prop types from Shadcn.
- **Rule (Import Location):** Never import HTML element attribute types (like `HTMLAttributes`, `HTMLButtonAttributes`, `SVGAttributes`, etc.) from `'svelte'`. They **must** be imported from `'svelte/elements'` (e.g. `import type { HTMLAttributes } from 'svelte/elements'`). Svelte-specific template utilities (like `Snippet` or `Component`) are imported from `'svelte'`.
- **Class Passing Syntax:** Use an array to merge base classes and custom classes passed via props:

  ```svelte
  <script lang="ts">
  	import type { HTMLAttributes } from 'svelte/elements';

  	let { class: className, children, ...restProps }: HTMLAttributes<HTMLDivElement> = $props();
  </script>

  <div class={['original-class', className]} {...restProps}>
  	{@render children?.()}
  </div>
  ```

- **Usage Flexibility:** This allows users of your components to pass classes as strings, arrays, or objects:
  ```svelte
  <CustomComponent class={{ 'bg-blue-700 sm:w-1/2': isActive }} />
  ```

## 4. Keyed Each Blocks

- **Rule:** Every `{#each}` block written must provide a key to ensure proper keyed rendering.
- **Key Uniqueness:** Make sure the key is unique (e.g., database IDs).
- **Fallback:** If a unique database or logic key is not available, use the loop index as the key.
- **Example:**

  ```svelte
  {#each items as item, index (item.id)}
  	<p>{item.name}</p>
  {/each}

  <!-- Fallback using index -->
  {#each simpleList as name, index (index)}
  	<p>{name}</p>
  {/each}
  ```

## 5. Icon Imports

- **Rule:** Always import icons inside a module script tag (`<script lang="ts" module>`), never inside the normal component script tag.
- **Import Syntax:** Icons must be imported individually as default imports. Do NOT use destructured imports.
- **Example:**
  ```svelte
  <script lang="ts" module>
  	// GOOD: Individual default imports
  	import ArrowUpIcon from '@lucide/svelte/icons/arrow-up';
  </script>
  ```
- **Never Do This:**
  ```svelte
  <script lang="ts" module>
  	// BAD: Destructured imports from the main entrypoint
  	import { ArrowUp, Globe } from '@lucide/svelte';
  </script>
  ```
- **Passing & Typing Icons dynamically:** When storing icons in data arrays or passing them as props, use Svelte 5 component typing. Ensure imports are still in the module script:

  ```svelte
  <script lang="ts" module>
  	import HomeIcon from '@lucide/svelte/icons/home';
  	import LibraryIcon from '@lucide/svelte/icons/library';
  	import CogIcon from '@lucide/svelte/icons/cog';
  </script>

  <script lang="ts">
  	import type { Component } from 'svelte';

  	type MenuItem = {
  		name: string;
  		href: string;
  		icon: Component;
  	};

  	const menuItems: MenuItem[] = [
  		{
  			name: 'Home',
  			href: '/',
  			icon: HomeIcon
  		},
  		{
  			name: 'Blog',
  			href: '/blog',
  			icon: LibraryIcon
  		},
  		{
  			name: 'Projects',
  			href: '/projects',
  			icon: CogIcon
  		}
  	];
  </script>

  {#each menuItems as item, index (item.name)}
  	{@const Icon = item.icon}
  	<a href={item.href}>
  		<Icon />
  		<span>{item.name}</span>
  	</a>
  {/each}
  ```

## 6. Svelte Local Declaration Tags

- **Rule:** Declaration tags define local variables inside markup with `const` or `let`:

<!-- codeblock:start {"title":"Declaration tags"} -->
```svelte
<!--- file: App.svelte --->
<script>
	let boxes = [{ width: 10, height: 10 }, { width: 15, height: 15 }];
</script>

{#each boxes as box}
	{const area = box.width * box.height}
	{const label = `${box.width} ⨉ ${box.height} = ${area}`}

	<p>{label}</p>
{/each}
```
<!-- codeblock:end -->

> [!NOTE] Declaration tags are available since Svelte 5.56.

> [!NOTE] The [`{@const ...}`](@const) syntax is considered legacy — use declaration tags instead.

When values should be reactive, you can use `$state` and `$derived`:

<!-- codeblock:start {"title":"Reactive declaration tags"} -->
```svelte
<!--- file: App.svelte --->
<script>
	let user = $state({ name: 'Svelte' });
	let editing = $state(false);
</script>

<p>Hello {user.name}</p>
<button onclick={() => editing = true}>edit name</button>

{#if editing}
	{let name = $state(user.name)}
	{const greeting = $derived(`Hello ${name}`)}

	<hr>
	<input bind:value={name} />
	<p>{greeting}</p>

	<button onclick={() => {
		user.name = name;
		editing = false;
	}}>save</button>
{/if}
```
<!-- codeblock:end -->

Declaration tags can be used anywhere inside the component. They can reference values declared outside themselves (for example in the `<script>` tag or in `{#each ...}` blocks) and are 'visible' to everything in the same lexical scope (i.e. siblings, and children of those siblings):

<!-- codeblock:start {"title":"Declaration tag scope"} -->
```svelte
<!--- file: App.svelte --->
{const hello = 'hello'}
{hello} <!-- 'hello' -->
<div>
	{const hello = 'hi'}
	{hello} <!-- 'hi' -->
	<div>
		{hello} <!-- 'hi' -->
	</div>
</div>
{hello} <!-- 'hello' -->
```
<!-- codeblock:end -->


## 7. Keep Clean Separation

- Keep `src/lib/components/ui/` pure and vendor-managed.
- Keep `src/lib/components/app/` for project-specific custom components, compositions, and overrides.

## 8. Typed Links & Route Resolution

- **Rule:** When rendering links or defining paths for `href` attributes, always resolve them using the `resolve` function from `$app/paths` for better TypeScript typing and to handle base paths correctly.
- **Typing:** Use types like `Pathname`, `RouteIdWithSearchOrHash`, or `PathnameWithSearchOrHash` from `$app/types` when defining path/URL parameters or component props.
- **Example/Docs:**

  ```ts
  import { resolve } from '$app/paths';

  // using a pathname
  const resolved = resolve(`/blog/hello-world`);

  // using a route ID plus parameters
  const resolved = resolve('/blog/[slug]', {
  	slug: 'hello-world'
  });
  ```

  Signature:
  ```ts
  function resolve<
  	T extends
  		| RouteIdWithSearchOrHash
  		| PathnameWithSearchOrHash
  >(...args: ResolveArgs<T>): ResolvedPathname;
  ```

- **Localization Example (Casting to `Pathname`):**
  When using localization libraries (like paraglide) that dynamicize paths, cast localized URLs to `Pathname` from `$app/types` before passing them to `resolve()`:

  ```svelte
  <script lang="ts">
  	import type { Pathname } from '$app/types';
  	import { resolve } from '$app/paths';
  	import { page } from '$app/state';
  	import { locales, localizeHref } from '$lib/paraglide/runtime';
  	import favicon from '$lib/assets/favicon.svg';

  	let { children } = $props();
  </script>

  <svelte:head><link rel="icon" href={favicon} /></svelte:head>
  {@render children()}

  <div style="display:none">
  	{#each locales as locale (locale)}
  		<a
  			href={resolve(localizeHref(page.url.pathname, { locale }) as Pathname)}
  		>{locale}</a>
  	{/each}
  </div>
  ```
